 her the best way possible and I will whether it be in a private school or a public school.  That is my choice.  Also, religion is not a less compelling reason to send a child to private school.  People wanted separation of church and state, which I agree, but I want my child to have an education with an influence of God and should not feel compelled just to provide that on Sundays.  BTW - most private schools have robust scholarship programs so those without money can attend...that's what makes them great and diverse...they value all and can say so. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="864" language="en" documentId="3201" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Product of public education -parent of private" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:34PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="36" thumbsDown="0" origId="3201" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="864"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>